+# Fix for `delay(Duration)` incorrectly coercing nanoseconds and microseconds
+
+## Problem
+
+The `delay(Duration)` function was truncating durations to milliseconds, losing nanosecond and microsecond precision. This caused delays to be shorter than requested when the duration had sub-millisecond components.
+
+**Example**: Delaying with `998.milliseconds + 902752.nanoseconds` would be truncated to `998ms` instead of the proper `999ms`, causing jobs scheduled with precise timing to invoke early.
+
+## Root Cause
+
+The issue was in the `toDelayMillis()` function in `kotlinx-coroutines-core/common/src/Delay.kt`:
+
+```kotlin
+// OLD IMPLEMENTATION (INCORRECT)
+internal fun Duration.toDelayMillis(): Long =
+    if (this > Duration.ZERO) inWholeMilliseconds.coerceAtLeast(1) else 0
+```
+
+This implementation truncated durations to whole milliseconds, discarding any nanosecond/microsecond components.
+
+## Solution
+
+The fix rounds up to the next whole millisecond when there's any sub-millisecond component, ensuring the delay is at least as long as requested:
+
+```kotlin
+// NEW IMPLEMENTATION (CORRECT)
+internal fun Duration.toDelayMillis(): Long =
+    if (this > Duration.ZERO) {
+        val millis = inWholeMilliseconds
+        // Round up if there is any sub-millisecond component
+        if (millis * 1_000_000 < inWholeNanoseconds) millis + 1 else millis
+    } else 0
+```
+
+The logic:
+1. Get the whole milliseconds (e.g., 998ms from 998.902752ms)
+2. Multiply by 1,000,000 to convert to nanoseconds (998,000,000 ns)
+3. Compare with actual nanoseconds (998,902,752 ns)
+4. If there's any sub-millisecond nanosecond remainder, increment the millisecond count (999ms)
+
+## Impact
+
+This fix affects all functions that use `toDelayMillis()`:
+- `delay(Duration)` - suspending delay function
+- `withTimeout(Duration)` - timeout with exception
+- `withTimeoutOrNull(Duration)` - timeout without exception  
+- `onTimeout(Duration)` - select clause
+- Flow operators: `debounce(Duration)`, `sample(Duration)`
+
+All these functions now correctly handle durations with sub-millisecond precision by rounding up to ensure delays are at least as long as requested.
+
+## Testing
+
+Created comprehensive test suite in `DelayRoundingTest.kt` covering:
+1. Rounding behavior with various sub-millisecond components
+2. Edge cases (zero, negative, exact millisecond values)
+3. Integration tests verifying actual delay duration meets expectations

